## Daily Fruit & Vegetable Intake





::: {.cell layout-align="center"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Figure 8.2. Daily Fruit & Vegetable Intake (n=1810, 86% of 2110 reporting).](Eating_Habits_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-5-1.png){fig-align='center' width=576}
:::
:::





**Survey Question:** [*How many servings of fruits and vegetables do you usually consume per day? (1 serving= 1 medium piece of fruit; 1/2 cup fresh, frozen, or canned fruits/vegetables; 1 cup salad greens; or 1/4 cup dried fruit). Do NOT include fruit juices.^1^*](#Footnotes)


**Summary:** A total of 226 (12.5%) students reported usually eating zero servings of fruits and vegetables per day, 1320 (72.9%) reported eating one to two servings per day, 233 (12.9%) reported eating three to four servings per day, and only 31 (1.7%) reported eating five or more servings per day.

<br />



## Daily Sugar-Sweetened Beverage Intake





::: {.cell layout-align="center"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Figure 8.3. Daily Sugar Sweetened Beverage Intake (n=1838, 87% of 2110 reporting).](Eating_Habits_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-6-1.png){fig-align='center' width=576}
:::
:::




**Survey Question:** *How many ounces of regular soda/cola/pop, sports drinks, energy drinks, or sweetened coffee and tea beverages do you consume each day? Do NOT count diet or zero-calorie drinks. Consider 8 ounces is 1 cup/glass of soda; 1 can of soda is 12 ounces; 1 bottle of juice is typically 16-20 ounces; 2 Liter bottle of soda is 68 oz; 1 Liter sweetened iced tea is 34 oz*


**Summary:** A total of 628 (34.2%) students reported drinking zero servings of sugar-sweetened beverages per day, 684 (37.2%) reported drinking one to eight ounces per day, and 326 (17.7%) reported drinking nine to 16 ounces per day. The remaining 200 (10.9%) students reported drinking 17 or more ounces per day.


<br />

## Weekly Fast Food Intake




::: {.cell layout-align="center"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Figure 8.4. Weekly Fast Food Intake (n=1843, 87% of 2110 reporting).](Eating_Habits_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-7-1.png){fig-align='center' width=576}
:::
:::




**Survey Question:** *How frequently do you eat from fast food restaurants, convenience stores, or vending machines for a meal or meal replacement?*

**Summary:** A total of 259 (14.1%) students reported eating fast food zero times per week, 1031 (55.9%) reported eating fast food one to two times per week, 407 (22.1%) reported eating fast food three to four times, and the remaining 146 (7.9%) reported eating fast food five or more times per week. 


<br />

## Weekly Alcohol Intake {#Weekly-Alcohol-Intake}





::: {.cell layout-align="center"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Figure 8.5. Weekly Alcohol Intake (n=1832, 87% of 2110 reporting).](Eating_Habits_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-8-1.png){fig-align='center' width=576}
:::
:::




**Survey Question:** [*How often do you consume at least one serving of alcohol? (1 serving= 12 ounces of beer, a 5-ounce glass of wine, or a drink containing 1 shot of liquor or hard alcohol).^2^*](#Footnotes)

**Summary:** A total of 1501 (81.9%) reported drinking alcohol zero times per week, 272 (14.8%) reported drinking alcohol one to two days a week, and the remaining 59 (3.2%) reported drinking alcohol three or more days per week. 

<br />

## Alcohol Servings Consumed





::: {.cell layout-align="center"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Figure 8.6. Alcohol Servings Consumed When Drinking (n=318, 15% of 2110 reporting).](Eating_Habits_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-9-1.png){fig-align='center' width=576}
:::
:::




**Survey Question:** [*Typically, how many servings of alcohol do you consume when you drink alcohol? (1 serving = 12 ounces of beer, a 5-ounce glass of wine, or a drink containing 1 shot of liquor or hard alcohol).^2^*](#Footnotes)

**Additional Notes:** This question was displayed only to students who reported drinking alcohol one or more times per week (see [Weekly Alcohol Intake](#Weekly-Alcohol-Intake)).


**Summary:** Of the students that reported drinking at least once per week, 49 (15.4%) reported drinking less than one serving when they drink, 150 (47.2%) reported drinking one to two servings, 83 (26.1%) reported drinking three to four servings, and 36 (11.3%) reported drinking five or more servings. 



<br />

## Cooking Confidence




::: {.cell layout-align="center"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Figure 8.7. Cooking Confidence.](Eating_Habits_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-10-1.png){fig-align='center' width=768}
:::
:::





**Survey Question:** [*The following questions pertain to how comfortable you feel about buying or preparing food:^3^*](#Footnotes)

**Summary:** Overall, the majority of students feel confident in their cooking habits. A notable 644 (34.6%) students were neutral, not very confident, or not at all confident that they can use the same healthy ingredients in more than one meal; 352 (18.8%) were neutral, not very confident, or not at all confident that they can use basic cooking skills; 740 (39.8%) were neutral, not very confident, or not at all confident that they can buy healthy food for their family on a budget; and 749 (40.2%) were neutral, not very confident, or not at all confident that they can cook healthy meals for their family on a budget. 

